					<description><![CDATA[<p>Twinco Capital has successfully closed a combined €165 million financing package. The dual-structured transaction marks a historic milestone for the global trade finance sector, effectively institutionalising purchase order financing as</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/twinco-secures-e165m-to-scale-trade-finance-model/" data-wpel-link="internal">Twinco Secures €165M to Scale Trade Finance Model</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.twincocapital.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Twinco Capital </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has successfully closed a combined €165 million </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/blackstone-raises-13-1b-in-major-fund-boost/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">financing </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">package. The dual-structured transaction marks a historic milestone for the global trade finance sector, effectively institutionalising purchase order financing as a scalable, low-risk asset class for the first time. The massive capital influx comprises two distinct financial tracks: a €15 million Series B equity funding round and a groundbreaking €150 million securitisation facility. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The equity portion was led by FMO, the Dutch entrepreneurial development bank, alongside a new strategic investment from Spanish banking group Bankinter. Returning prominent venture backers, including Quona Capital and the Working Capital Fund, also participated in the round, bringing Twinco&#8217;s total equity backing to approximately $73 million.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Simultaneously, the landmark €150 million securitisation facility was structured and led entirely by Banco Santander, one of the largest financial institutions in the world.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Rewriting the Rules of Supply Chain Finance</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Founded in 2016 by Sandra Nolasco (CEO) and Carmen Marín (COO), Twinco Capital has addressed a massive structural flaw in how global trade is financed. While the multi-billion-dollar supply chain finance industry has spent two decades digitalising invoices, traditional factoring and invoice financing options only kick in </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400">after</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400"> goods have already been manufactured, shipped, and invoiced.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">However, mid-sized and small suppliers, particularly those based in developing economies across Latin America, Asia, and Eastern Europe, require heavy working capital long before an invoice exists. They need cash to purchase raw materials, fund labour, and keep factory floors moving from the exact moment a buyer issues a purchase order. Twinco completely bridges this liquidity gap by funding up to 60% of a purchase order&#8217;s value upfront, with the remaining balance cleared immediately upon delivery.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_202249" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202249" class="size-large wp-image-202249" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/coins-in-a-jar-1024x683.jpg" alt="coins in a jar" width="1024" height="683" /><p id="caption-attachment-202249" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;Global supply chains depend on suppliers having access to liquidity long before goods are delivered and invoices are issued,&#8221; said Sandra Nolasco, co-founder and CEO of Twinco. &#8220;Yet traditional supply chain finance still largely begins at the invoice stage. What Twinco offers is fundamentally different: a technology and risk platform capable of financing and managing execution risk from the moment a purchase order is issued.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/blackstone-raises-13-1b-in-major-fund-boost/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Blackstone Raises $13.1B in Major Fund Boost</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">A Proven Algorithm with Zero Losses</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Historically, global commercial banks have avoided purchase order financing because underwriting pre-shipment transactions is incredibly complex and operationally risky. If a supplier fails to manufacture or deliver the goods, the lender faces total default.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Twinco bypasses this risk by substituting traditional, rigid balance-sheet credit assessments with a proprietary risk intelligence model. Instead of looking solely at a supplier&#8217;s net worth or historical banking records, Twinco&#8217;s platform ingests real-time operational data, assessing the strength of commercial relationships and evaluating historical production reliability. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Essentially, the platform calculates whether a supplier will successfully deliver the ordered goods, rather than just checking if an invoice is legally valid. The approach has proven remarkably bulletproof. Since launching its active commercial footprint in 2019, Twinco has processed over $1 billion in trade transactions across 25 countries with an unprecedented record of zero losses.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This flawless underwriting track record is precisely what enabled Banco Santander to successfully structure the €150 million securitisation fund, an achievement previously considered impossible for pre-shipment trade assets.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Fueling Global Scale and AI Capabilities</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Twinco operates at an institutional scale, partnering with high-profile multinational retail and consumer goods corporations to fund their vast, global supplier networks. Current enterprise clients include fashion retail giants Mango in Spain and Lojas Renner in Brazil, Centric Brands in the United States, and children&#8217;s e-commerce retailer Vertbaudet in France.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">According to Co-founder and COO Carmen Marín, the €15 million equity injection will be weaponised to scale their engineering teams and further automate their underwriting capabilities. Specifically, the fintech is embedding specialized machine learning and artificial intelligence (AI) layers on top of its data models to accurately predict supplier performance and detect potential disruption vectors across international supply corridors.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;This transaction represents an important evolution for the industry: bringing institutional capital into purchase order finance at scale for the first time through a securitisation structure,&#8221; noted Enrique Rico, Global Head of Trade &amp; Working Capital Solutions at Banco Santander.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">As geopolitical tensions and climate disruptions continue to stress-test international commerce, the broader purchase order financing market is projected to swell from $5.5 billion to nearly $12.9 billion by 2033. Backed by institutional-grade capital and major European banking syndicates, Twinco is positioned to capture a major share of this expanding asset class.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/twinco-secures-e165m-to-scale-trade-finance-model/" data-wpel-link="internal">Twinco Secures €165M to Scale Trade Finance Model</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
